1
00:00:07,009 --> 00:00:11,846
All right, so,
we should talk about this immediately.

2
00:00:11,971 --> 00:00:13,182
Who are you, by the way?

3
00:00:13,307 --> 00:00:15,141
- I'm J.J. Who are you?
- I'm Damon.

4
00:00:15,266 --> 00:00:17,643
- Where's Bob?
- Hey, I'm over here. Hi, guys.

5
00:00:17,768 --> 00:00:19,437
- Alex, you around?
- I'm right here.

6
00:00:19,562 --> 00:00:21,899
- So this piece of music...
- Bryan Burk, sound off.

7
00:00:22,024 --> 00:00:24,693
- Is Bryan there?
- Hi. I'm here. I'm in New York.

8
00:00:24,818 --> 00:00:27,905
- This is ridiculous.
- Bryan is joining us via satellite today.

9
00:00:28,030 --> 00:00:31,824
This music was not the original piece
of music in this opening sequence.

10
00:00:33,159 --> 00:00:35,161
Michael Giacchino had this recorded

11
00:00:35,286 --> 00:00:37,664
like two weeks before
we finished the mix,

12
00:00:37,789 --> 00:00:41,960
- and I think this is a genius move.
- Unbelievably awesome.

13
00:00:42,085 --> 00:00:45,463
It's great 'cause it makes
the Bad Robot logo really creepy.

14
00:00:46,756 --> 00:00:48,884
- It does. It's very ominous.
- It is scary.

15
00:00:49,009 --> 00:00:51,427
- For the first time ever that robot...
- Is actually bad.

16
00:00:51,552 --> 00:00:53,054
...freaks me out.

17
00:00:58,060 --> 00:00:59,936
The movie didn't originally
open with this.

18
00:01:00,061 --> 00:01:03,148
- Nope.
- It opened with the birth of Spock.

19
00:01:03,774 --> 00:01:07,986
And why was it changed, J. J?

20
00:01:08,820 --> 00:01:11,823
Well, we had the birth of Spock.
Then we had the birth of Kirk.

21
00:01:11,989 --> 00:01:14,367
Then we had young Spock,
then young Kirk.

22
00:01:14,492 --> 00:01:16,328
Then we had older Spock,
then older Kirk.

23
00:01:16,453 --> 00:01:19,831
And it just was too much back and forth
for too long,

24
00:01:19,956 --> 00:01:23,918
so we removed the birth of Spock

25
00:01:24,585 --> 00:01:28,006
and made the Kirk birth sequence
a pre-credit sequence

26
00:01:28,132 --> 00:01:31,926
to kind of reset the movie, which I think
helped the pace of the open.

27
00:01:32,051 --> 00:01:35,097
I can't imagine the movie
starting any other way than this.

28
00:01:35,222 --> 00:01:39,100
That's very funny because
we only debated it for a year and a half.

29
00:01:39,225 --> 00:01:40,811
- But until we all saw it...
- Until we saw it.

30
00:01:40,936 --> 00:01:43,063
- Until we saw it.
- Yeah.

31
00:01:43,188 --> 00:01:45,816
I mean, I think the thing
that's so genius about this is that

32
00:01:45,941 --> 00:01:49,069
you're dropping the audience
right into the middle of a situation

33
00:01:49,194 --> 00:01:51,405
and a terror that's so cool.

34
00:01:51,530 --> 00:01:54,365
That was Randy Pausch, by the way,
who walked right past Robau.

35
00:01:54,490 --> 00:01:57,411
We were also really concerned
about canon and continuity,

36
00:01:57,536 --> 00:01:59,246
because Spock is older than Kirk.

37
00:01:59,371 --> 00:02:01,915
- Right. That's right.
- So you couldn't do this scene first,

38
00:02:02,040 --> 00:02:05,626
and then Spock's birth because of that.

39
00:02:05,878 --> 00:02:09,923
So, it was either start the movie
with this scene and lose Spock's birth,

40
00:02:10,048 --> 00:02:11,758
which was... We're basically like,

41
00:02:11,884 --> 00:02:13,801
"If we lose that,
we lose his attachment to his mother.

42
00:02:13,926 --> 00:02:15,929
"We don't understand
that his mom is human."

43
00:02:16,054 --> 00:02:18,431
Because in the other scene
that Winona is in,

44
00:02:18,556 --> 00:02:21,058
her ears are actually wrapped,

45
00:02:21,185 --> 00:02:24,562
so other than dialogue,
you don't know that she's a human.

46
00:02:24,854 --> 00:02:26,397
But enough about that.

47
00:02:26,522 --> 00:02:30,318
I love the way that the weapon systems
on the <i>Narada</i> work.

48
00:02:30,443 --> 00:02:33,739
The other thing that's genius for me
about this is the way you cut it.

49
00:02:34,281 --> 00:02:36,240
What's the <i>Kelvin</i> named after?
Oh, sorry.

50
00:02:36,408 --> 00:02:38,659
- I thought you were done.
- Kelvin was my grandfather. Sorry.

51
00:02:38,784 --> 00:02:41,954
Oh, yeah.
No, you should tell that story first.

52
00:02:42,456 --> 00:02:44,500
Harry Kelvin was my grandfather.

53
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:46,001
I love that story.

54
00:02:46,126 --> 00:02:47,920
I use his name in almost everything
that I've worked on.

55
00:02:48,045 --> 00:02:50,004
- That story gets me every time.
- Fade out.

56
00:02:50,421 --> 00:02:53,258
No, but he was the guy
who sort of inspired me

57
00:02:53,383 --> 00:02:56,844
to make movies and make things,
and have things work.

58
00:02:56,969 --> 00:02:58,388
So he was sort of the...

59
00:02:58,930 --> 00:03:01,974
Bryan Burk, was this your idea
for sound design, right here?

60
00:03:02,099 --> 00:03:03,185
I'd like to take credit for this,

61
00:03:03,310 --> 00:03:07,271
but this was J.J.'s sound design
from the very first cut.

62
00:03:07,396 --> 00:03:10,067
I love the idea that everything goes out

63
00:03:10,192 --> 00:03:12,819
when we enter
the cold vastness of space.

64
00:03:12,944 --> 00:03:16,865
Well, it's a weird thing 'cause I wanted
to do silent space from the beginning,

65
00:03:16,990 --> 00:03:19,909
but the truth is it feels like
the movie's not completed

66
00:03:20,034 --> 00:03:21,495
when you actually
have silence in space.

67
00:03:21,620 --> 00:03:22,829
It feels like the weight is not there.

68
00:03:23,329 --> 00:03:27,292
I sort of did the, you know, occasional...

69
00:03:29,044 --> 00:03:31,003
Acknowledgement
that you're aware of reality.

70
00:03:31,129 --> 00:03:32,381
Yeah, that it sort of says that

71
00:03:32,506 --> 00:03:33,924
the reality is that there's silence
in space,

72
00:03:34,049 --> 00:03:37,510
but I wanted to, you know,
give the sequences,

73
00:03:37,635 --> 00:03:41,889
for the most part, the sound that
you would expect to feel in here.

74
00:03:43,057 --> 00:03:49,230
If you roll back, not us, but you,
the viewer, on the shot of the screen,

75
00:03:49,355 --> 00:03:51,316
- you'll see there's this...
- How could we roll back?

76
00:03:51,441 --> 00:03:52,985
Are you in a coffee can?

77
00:03:53,110 --> 00:03:55,736
There are these handrails,
which is really kind of a testament

78
00:03:55,862 --> 00:03:58,448
to Scott Chambliss,
our production designer,

79
00:03:58,574 --> 00:04:01,325
who really made the ship really tangible.

80
00:04:01,450 --> 00:04:03,871
And I remember being on set
with a friend who was visiting,

81
00:04:03,996 --> 00:04:06,122
who was commenting that
when you think about it,

82
00:04:06,247 --> 00:04:08,000
and you're flying through space
and you're bouncing around,

83
00:04:08,125 --> 00:04:10,461
just the fact that these are here
and you can hold on to them

84
00:04:10,586 --> 00:04:13,546
is something that you would assume
would be on all spaceships.

85
00:04:13,671 --> 00:04:16,341
And I can't remember seeing it
in another film.

86
00:04:16,466 --> 00:04:17,509
There they are.

87
00:04:17,634 --> 00:04:20,762
I love the way that Robau there says,
"You're the captain now, Mr Kirk."

88
00:04:20,887 --> 00:04:24,557
Because if you've never seen
<i>Star Trek</i> before, or if you have,

89
00:04:24,682 --> 00:04:26,768
in that moment, watching this movie,
you're like,

90
00:04:26,935 --> 00:04:29,187
"That's Kirk.
I've just been introduced to Kirk."

91
00:04:29,312 --> 00:04:32,149
Because you've never seen
Chris Pine before.

92
00:04:32,274 --> 00:04:35,819
And the actor that we cast looks enough

93
00:04:35,944 --> 00:04:38,654
- like Chris Pine that you're like...
- My sister thought it was Chris Pine.

94
00:04:38,779 --> 00:04:41,492
She said to me, "Why did you cast
the same actor as the father and Kirk?"

95
00:04:41,617 --> 00:04:43,701
- Right.
- It's like, "I didn't."

96
00:04:44,202 --> 00:04:46,329
The thing is
this is one of my favourite sequences

97
00:04:46,454 --> 00:04:51,959
because this was shot, literally all
of this if you include the CG stuff,

98
00:04:52,084 --> 00:04:53,545
months if not over a year apart.

99
00:04:53,670 --> 00:04:56,798
So, you know,
Robau going from the Bridge,

100
00:04:56,923 --> 00:04:59,968
which we shot at Paramount,
to going down the turbo lift,

101
00:05:00,093 --> 00:05:02,637
which was shot at a power plant
in Long Beach,

102
00:05:02,762 --> 00:05:06,098
to his walking down the corridor
and into the shuttle,

103
00:05:06,225 --> 00:05:09,394
which we shot in two different locations
back at Paramount.

104
00:05:09,519 --> 00:05:14,274
You know, all these sequences
have dozens if not hundreds of pieces

105
00:05:14,399 --> 00:05:16,526
that are shot so far apart.

106
00:05:16,651 --> 00:05:18,612
It's just the fun of filmmaking
seeing them all come together.

107
00:05:18,737 --> 00:05:22,031
And so how much in prep
did you end up...

108
00:05:22,156 --> 00:05:24,492
I mean, what of it was improvised
and what of it was prep?

109
00:05:24,617 --> 00:05:26,161
- Was all of it prep?
- Well, in general,

110
00:05:27,161 --> 00:05:33,334
what I tried to do is prep as little
specifics as possible in terms of shots.

111
00:05:33,459 --> 00:05:36,838
So, I wanted to be able to go to the set
and make things up as I went along,

112
00:05:36,963 --> 00:05:38,841
and sort of, you know, wing it.

113
00:05:38,966 --> 00:05:42,136
But then there are certain sequences,
like the space jump that come later

114
00:05:42,261 --> 00:05:44,471
and some of the <i>Kelvin</i> attack,

115
00:05:44,596 --> 00:05:46,807
that we needed to know
what we needed to build.

116
00:05:46,932 --> 00:05:52,103
So, within the parameters
of what we had, you know,

117
00:05:52,228 --> 00:05:55,481
I tried to storyboard nothing
so that the thing would have an energy

118
00:05:55,606 --> 00:05:59,528
and would feel vital, and we get
to make it up as we went along.

119
00:05:59,653 --> 00:06:03,031
And yet, certain things we needed
to know how we were physically

120
00:06:03,156 --> 00:06:04,783
ever gonna do them.
I remember the first time

121
00:06:04,908 --> 00:06:06,660
they saw the space jump,
they were like, "What?"

122
00:06:06,785 --> 00:06:09,036
- Right.
- "Forget it. We can't shoot this."

123
00:06:09,163 --> 00:06:11,372
I love Bana here.

124
00:06:11,497 --> 00:06:14,209
It's awesome
that he doesn't say a single word.

125
00:06:14,334 --> 00:06:15,793
Yeah, he's terrific.

126
00:06:15,918 --> 00:06:20,923
I mean, I remember the first day
that I shot on this set,

127
00:06:21,048 --> 00:06:23,468
I literally just broke out in a sweat
because I was surrounded

128
00:06:23,593 --> 00:06:27,180
by all these bald dudes with face tattoos

129
00:06:27,305 --> 00:06:31,726
and pointy ears and the wardrobe.

130
00:06:31,851 --> 00:06:37,274
And I was so afraid
that it was gonna look insanely stupid.

131
00:06:37,399 --> 00:06:38,858
- I really was.
- My favourite cut

132
00:06:38,983 --> 00:06:40,485
is coming up right here.

133
00:06:42,696 --> 00:06:43,697
Now that's all one shot.
We actually cut it.

134
00:06:43,822 --> 00:06:45,115
Right here. The fact that you cut out

135
00:06:45,240 --> 00:06:46,408
- before he finishes his sentence.
- That's right.

136
00:06:46,533 --> 00:06:48,326
That is so great. That is my favourite.

137
00:06:48,451 --> 00:06:49,995
- I actually debated that.
- Can you talk about that?

138
00:06:50,120 --> 00:06:52,747
Because, literally, it is the most brilliant
editing choice ever.

139
00:06:52,872 --> 00:06:55,125
It was because he said it,
and then it cut, and I just thought,

140
00:06:55,250 --> 00:06:57,711
"You know what? Let's..." It just felt
like the energy of the moment

141
00:06:57,836 --> 00:06:59,213
- wanted to move ahead.
- Yeah. Yes.

142
00:06:59,338 --> 00:07:01,464
- It just was like...
- Because, you know,

143
00:07:01,589 --> 00:07:03,300
- it's just genius.
- Yeah, it's funny. I didn't know

144
00:07:03,425 --> 00:07:05,218
- you realised. That's hysterical.
- Are you kidding?

145
00:07:05,343 --> 00:07:09,514
It's funny because, you know, editorially,
Mary Jo and Maryann,

146
00:07:09,639 --> 00:07:12,893
it was this way on the <i>Lost</i> pilot, too.

147
00:07:13,018 --> 00:07:15,437
You basically spend 75% of your time

148
00:07:15,562 --> 00:07:17,980
editing a couple sequences
in one of these things,

149
00:07:18,105 --> 00:07:20,108
- and the other 30% on everything else.
- Yeah.

150
00:07:20,233 --> 00:07:22,235
And in this movie,

151
00:07:22,360 --> 00:07:25,072
it felt like every time I came
and visited the editing room,

152
00:07:25,197 --> 00:07:26,906
- you guys were working on the <i>Kelvin.</i>
- Yeah.

153
00:07:27,031 --> 00:07:31,536
And this was actually
Bryan's genius suggestion, as I recall...

154
00:07:31,661 --> 00:07:33,454
- Yeah.
...which was we,

155
00:07:33,579 --> 00:07:36,415
in the script
and in several cuts before this,

156
00:07:36,542 --> 00:07:42,422
introduced Kirk's mom
many, many scenes prior to this.

157
00:07:42,798 --> 00:07:45,591
And the idea to basically say,
we're gonna intro her here,

158
00:07:45,716 --> 00:07:48,427
the idea that she's pregnant,
I thought, was genius.

159
00:07:48,553 --> 00:07:49,221
I remember, Bryan, when you
brought that up, and I fought you on it.

160
00:07:49,221 --> 00:07:52,182
I remember, Bryan, when you
brought that up, and I fought you on it.

161
00:07:52,307 --> 00:07:54,768
I think we actually physically wrestled
in the editing room.

162
00:07:54,893 --> 00:07:58,896
But you were so smart,
because it engaged you,

163
00:07:59,021 --> 00:08:04,153
it let you engage in a deeper way,
on one level,

164
00:08:04,569 --> 00:08:06,904
and then, unexpectedly, it deepened it,

165
00:08:07,029 --> 00:08:10,908
as opposed to kind of telegraphing
what the story was gonna be.

166
00:08:11,033 --> 00:08:13,161
- I think it was a smart...
- You're already so into the sequence,

167
00:08:13,286 --> 00:08:16,831
it's so insane, and then it
just ratchets up the stakes 10,000%

168
00:08:16,956 --> 00:08:19,042
when you realise
there's a pregnant woman on the ship,

169
00:08:19,168 --> 00:08:21,836
and subliminally start to realise
that this must be Kirk in there.

170
00:08:21,961 --> 00:08:24,255
It just bifurcated the focus,
having it earlier.

171
00:08:24,380 --> 00:08:27,300
And, Bryan,
you want to talk about that or no?

172
00:08:28,302 --> 00:08:31,596
For me, I mean,
Jennifer has this one sequence here

173
00:08:31,721 --> 00:08:33,724
where she's so powerful and emotional,

174
00:08:33,849 --> 00:08:37,394
and you're completely moved by her
in this one moment.

175
00:08:37,519 --> 00:08:39,897
And it felt like, you know,

176
00:08:40,855 --> 00:08:45,943
this alone was able to carry the birth
of Kirk and it was kind of heartbreaking.

177
00:08:46,068 --> 00:08:48,279
And I remember,
one of the things that we talked about

178
00:08:48,404 --> 00:08:49,822
early in the development of the script,

179
00:08:49,947 --> 00:08:52,951
and this is a place where I really dug in
and was dead wrong,

180
00:08:53,076 --> 00:08:57,206
was that she doesn't
make it off the <i>Kelvin,</i>

181
00:08:58,331 --> 00:09:00,082
that Kirk needs to be beamed.

182
00:09:00,208 --> 00:09:02,293
There was a whole thing
where basically,

183
00:09:02,418 --> 00:09:04,379
in a emergency scenario,
like a caesarean,

184
00:09:04,504 --> 00:09:06,465
you could actually beam a baby
out of a mother's womb.

185
00:09:06,590 --> 00:09:07,966
We wrote that version. Yeah.

186
00:09:08,091 --> 00:09:11,010
But if you did it, you kill her
because it's an inexact science.

187
00:09:11,135 --> 00:09:12,596
Which is a really cool idea.

188
00:09:12,721 --> 00:09:16,975
But the idea that...
We ended up playing it straight,

189
00:09:17,100 --> 00:09:19,977
that it was a conventional birth
that everybody could identify with,

190
00:09:20,102 --> 00:09:22,773
and that the first time that you actually
use the transporter in the movie

191
00:09:22,898 --> 00:09:24,274
- is in the space jump.
- Right.

192
00:09:24,399 --> 00:09:28,153
Where we didn't overuse
our beaming gags,

193
00:09:28,278 --> 00:09:30,113
I think was really smart.

194
00:09:30,239 --> 00:09:32,365
More importantly, she survives.

195
00:09:32,490 --> 00:09:36,620
You know, which is really important.
There is a victory.

196
00:09:36,745 --> 00:09:42,292
Well, it's funny, because we ended up
cutting a sequence later

197
00:09:42,417 --> 00:09:44,961
where you saw their uncle,

198
00:09:45,086 --> 00:09:48,005
who now in this film
became the stepfather,

199
00:09:48,131 --> 00:09:51,134
the question is sort of
what role she played.

200
00:09:52,344 --> 00:09:54,053
It was an interesting thing,
'cause there was a while

201
00:09:54,178 --> 00:09:57,515
where she was on the phone call,
and she was mad at Kirk.

202
00:09:57,640 --> 00:10:00,184
And it felt like... You love her so much
from this sequence,

203
00:10:00,309 --> 00:10:04,148
that to have her being mean to Kirk later
felt counterintuitive.

204
00:10:04,273 --> 00:10:06,274
It felt like, "I don't want to not like her.
I just loved her."

205
00:10:06,399 --> 00:10:08,902
So, we ended up
having it just be the stepfather.

206
00:10:09,027 --> 00:10:12,614
But, I think, you know, given how
few minutes she's actually onscreen,

207
00:10:12,739 --> 00:10:14,283
I think Jennifer Morrison
did an amazing job.

208
00:10:14,408 --> 00:10:17,536
And I think, you know, for us,
for the five of us,

209
00:10:17,661 --> 00:10:20,956
when we first started talking about <i>Trek,</i>
I remember in the very first meeting,

210
00:10:21,081 --> 00:10:23,500
probably about five minutes in,
we basically said,

211
00:10:23,625 --> 00:10:27,379
"How in God's name are we gonna get
our wives to go and see this movie

212
00:10:27,504 --> 00:10:29,465
"other than the fact
that they're married to us?"

213
00:10:29,590 --> 00:10:33,384
You know, we will not be successful
in rebooting <i>Trek</i>

214
00:10:33,509 --> 00:10:36,221
unless we can get women
to enjoy the movie.

215
00:10:36,346 --> 00:10:38,682
And that's where I feel like...

216
00:10:39,349 --> 00:10:41,476
At least the birth of Spock
really had that going for it.

217
00:10:41,601 --> 00:10:43,979
But opening the movie with this
and kind of saying,

218
00:10:44,104 --> 00:10:46,230
in the midst of all this
space battle craziness,

219
00:10:46,355 --> 00:10:49,359
this is what the movie is, you know.

220
00:10:49,485 --> 00:10:51,320
This is the moment where my wife,

221
00:10:51,445 --> 00:10:53,238
when she first saw it,
sort of grabbed my hand,

222
00:10:53,363 --> 00:10:56,616
and I looked over at her
and her eyes were all moist,

223
00:10:56,741 --> 00:11:00,203
and I was like, "Okay.
I think maybe this is gonna work."

224
00:11:00,328 --> 00:11:03,956
And from a canon point of view,
this is the first canon divergence.

225
00:11:04,081 --> 00:11:06,585
- Whereas Kirk was always born in lowa.
