And I think they did an amazing job.

2411
01:54:15,481 --> 01:54:16,692
Amazing.
Like, kind of shockingly, actually.

2412
01:54:16,817 --> 01:54:18,694
Yeah, yeah. Really amazing.

2413
01:54:22,197 --> 01:54:24,949
In other words, he watched
<i>Back to the Future</i> too many times.

2414
01:54:25,074 --> 01:54:28,912
And by the way, most of the time
in time-travel movies,

2415
01:54:29,037 --> 01:54:31,707
when you are talking
to an older version of yourself,

2416
01:54:31,832 --> 01:54:34,083
the same actor is playing both roles.

2417
01:54:34,208 --> 01:54:37,880
The fact that we didn't do that,
and this is Nimoy,

2418
01:54:38,005 --> 01:54:39,131
who used to play Spock, and Quinto,

2419
01:54:39,256 --> 01:54:43,301
who is going to be playing Spock
for the indefinite foreseeable future,

2420
01:54:43,426 --> 01:54:45,636
you know, I think was...
Are we keeping you awake?

2421
01:54:45,762 --> 01:54:46,930
- Who was that?
- What was that?

2422
01:54:47,055 --> 01:54:49,265
- It was me, breathing.
- That was amazing.

2423
01:54:49,390 --> 01:54:50,641
I'm so sorry. Was it too loud?

2424
01:54:50,768 --> 01:54:53,895
I thought the airlock just leaked.
Seriously.

2425
01:54:54,020 --> 01:54:57,064
Somebody wake Alex. Jeez.
It's unbelievable.

2426
01:54:57,190 --> 01:54:58,942
- Sorry. What were you saying?
- I don't remember.

2427
01:54:59,067 --> 01:55:00,444
It was putting me to sleep.

2428
01:55:01,528 --> 01:55:02,988
These are two different actors
playing the same part.

2429
01:55:03,113 --> 01:55:04,405
Yes, exactly.

2430
01:55:04,530 --> 01:55:06,949
There's something about
Michael J. Fox playing, you know,

2431
01:55:07,074 --> 01:55:08,993
- Marty McFly at 45...
- Yeah.

2432
01:55:09,118 --> 01:55:11,371
...where you go, "I don't buy it."

2433
01:55:11,497 --> 01:55:15,583
If you notice, Zachary's right hand
needed to be glued together,

2434
01:55:15,708 --> 01:55:18,045
his fingers, 'cause he couldn't do that
with his right hand.

2435
01:55:18,170 --> 01:55:19,296
Wow.

2436
01:55:20,213 --> 01:55:22,800
Another one of my favourite lines
in the movie is the,

2437
01:55:22,925 --> 01:55:27,179
"Since my customary farewell
would be..."

2438
01:55:28,346 --> 01:55:31,641
- He still wishes himself luck, though.
- Yes. That's true.

2439
01:55:31,766 --> 01:55:33,101
This was great set extension,
I must say,

2440
01:55:33,226 --> 01:55:35,645
just for those who are keeping score.

2441
01:55:36,563 --> 01:55:37,730
There's Ben Binswagner
on the left again.

2442
01:55:37,855 --> 01:55:39,483
And once again, Tyler Perry.

2443
01:55:39,608 --> 01:55:41,400
We were shooting a scene once
and he didn't like his take.

2444
01:55:41,527 --> 01:55:45,447
He said, "Cut." He's like, "Oh, I'm sorry."
He's so used to directing himself.

2445
01:55:46,532 --> 01:55:47,990
Flare. Flare.

2446
01:55:49,408 --> 01:55:53,747
- In that case, flare in both senses.
- And now, here's another thing.

2447
01:55:53,872 --> 01:55:58,252
I remember when I first saw this
in the editing room, you read the script

2448
01:55:58,377 --> 01:56:03,047
when Pike says, "I am relieved,"
you go, "Wow, that is all Greenwood."

2449
01:56:03,172 --> 01:56:05,716
I mean, like, you just never really...

2450
01:56:07,176 --> 01:56:10,180
- Talk about a double entendre.
- He's terrific there.

2451
01:56:11,722 --> 01:56:14,309
And that wheelchair, yes,
ladies and gentlemen, does answer

2452
01:56:14,435 --> 01:56:16,353
yes and no with single beeps.

2453
01:56:18,063 --> 01:56:20,940
And literally, I'm not kidding you,
weighed, like, 4,000 pounds.

2454
01:56:21,065 --> 01:56:23,777
It was the worst wheelchair.

2455
01:56:23,902 --> 01:56:26,863
It was a beautiful look,
but it was ridiculously heavy.

2456
01:56:26,988 --> 01:56:30,533
I think what's so cool about
the way that the movie ends is that

2457
01:56:30,658 --> 01:56:33,369
people are smiling, sort of, wall-to-wall.

2458
01:56:33,494 --> 01:56:35,622
Like, you just get this great, you know,

2459
01:56:35,747 --> 01:56:37,875
when the movie ends,
everybody's so happy.

2460
01:56:38,000 --> 01:56:40,042
That's a very rare feeling
in movies these days.

2461
01:56:40,168 --> 01:56:43,796
This was Nimoy's...
He said, "Can I just say a line here?"

2462
01:56:44,506 --> 01:56:45,966
I said, "Sure."

2463
01:56:47,259 --> 01:56:49,595
And I love the bittersweet nature of that.

2464
01:56:50,304 --> 01:56:51,596
Come on.

2465
01:56:55,016 --> 01:56:57,728
Here it is. Nice.

2466
01:57:04,400 --> 01:57:08,697
Whatever. He used to say,
"Same ship, different day."

2467
01:57:11,617 --> 01:57:12,951
That was the name of the file, actually.

2468
01:57:13,076 --> 01:57:15,787
This was a last-minute idea,
to have Keenser back on the thing.

2469
01:57:15,912 --> 01:57:17,206
So did you just call up Deep
and you were like...

2470
01:57:17,331 --> 01:57:19,457
We called Deep and said,
"Could you come today and shoot this?"

2471
01:57:19,582 --> 01:57:21,126
And so, that was a cut, actually.
We shot...

2472
01:57:21,251 --> 01:57:23,628
And he was like, "Fortunately,
I have not taken my makeup off,

2473
01:57:23,753 --> 01:57:25,380
"so I will be there."

2474
01:57:26,715 --> 01:57:29,635
It was funny. Shooting this scene,

2475
01:57:29,760 --> 01:57:33,596
you know, within the first weeks
of shooting,

2476
01:57:33,721 --> 01:57:35,765
- having not shot the whole film.
- Yeah, it's amazing.

2477
01:57:35,890 --> 01:57:39,811
And it was like trying to figure out
what should we be feeling here.

2478
01:57:39,936 --> 01:57:44,024
And again, I think that Chris and Zach
and the whole group just killed it.

2479
01:57:44,149 --> 01:57:45,317
They're so good.

2480
01:57:45,442 --> 01:57:47,027
Come on, look at the smile
on Sulu's face.

2481
01:57:47,152 --> 01:57:48,945
- This is my favourite.
- So, this moment...

2482
01:57:49,070 --> 01:57:50,655
- Happy that her boyfriend is on the ship.
- Yep.

2483
01:57:50,780 --> 01:57:51,907
It's spectacular.

2484
01:57:53,074 --> 01:57:54,243
She's so good there.

2485
01:57:55,409 --> 01:57:57,829
And there was debate
who to give these lines to.

2486
01:57:57,954 --> 01:57:59,914
Some people thought
we should give it to Shatner.

2487
01:58:00,039 --> 01:58:02,417
Some people thought
we should give it to Pine.

2488
01:58:02,542 --> 01:58:05,671
I just think, you know,
you gotta give it to Nimoy.

2489
01:58:06,255 --> 01:58:08,590
Well, you wanted to do it.

2490
01:58:08,715 --> 01:58:11,635
I did actually record a version. Joking.

2491
01:58:21,019 --> 01:58:23,855
And then these end credits, again,
are by that guy, Andrew Kramer,

2492
01:58:23,980 --> 01:58:27,650
who I just think did an amazing job.

2493
01:58:27,775 --> 01:58:29,819
It just, it looks so...

2494
01:58:30,028 --> 01:58:32,905
Yeah, I love the way that the camera
just sort of swoops around and...

2495
01:58:33,030 --> 01:58:36,326
This is like a two-minute sequence
of CG.

2496
01:58:36,452 --> 01:58:38,953
But is there a reason
you put our names over Uranus?

2497
01:58:39,872 --> 01:58:41,707
Wait, what'd you call me?

2498
01:58:41,832 --> 01:58:43,958
Well, his is over two big balls
over there, so that's...

2499
01:58:44,083 --> 01:58:45,293
Wait a second.

2500
01:58:45,418 --> 01:58:48,588
We made it through this entire
commentary and now we go blue?

2501
01:58:48,713 --> 01:58:50,591
- Now it's getting ugly.
- Wonderful.

2502
01:58:51,675 --> 01:58:54,136
Of course, Jeffrey Chernov, the...

2503
01:58:54,261 --> 01:58:56,054
Such a huge part of this movie,
by the way.

2504
01:58:56,180 --> 01:58:57,680
And by the way, there's a name that

2505
01:58:57,805 --> 01:58:59,807
we neglected to mention
during the commentary, but...

2506
01:58:59,932 --> 01:59:01,560
It wouldn't have happened without him.

2507
01:59:01,685 --> 01:59:03,270
- Essential member.
- The guy came in

2508
01:59:03,395 --> 01:59:06,856
literally six weeks before shooting
and took control of the production.

2509
01:59:06,981 --> 01:59:10,277
He said, "I need one week
to wrap my head around it,

2510
01:59:10,402 --> 01:59:12,820
"one week to figure it out,"
and then you know,

2511
01:59:12,945 --> 01:59:16,115
we started on schedule,
we finished on schedule.

2512
01:59:16,240 --> 01:59:18,118
And almost never said no.

2513
01:59:18,243 --> 01:59:20,871
He's amazing. He really is the greatest.

2514
01:59:20,996 --> 01:59:22,163
We discussed Roger Guyett.

2515
01:59:22,288 --> 01:59:25,792
Shari Hanson,
who also was just invaluable.

2516
01:59:26,460 --> 01:59:27,502
David Witz was an amazing producer.

2517
01:59:27,627 --> 01:59:28,796
We should just name
everyone we're seeing.

2518
01:59:28,921 --> 01:59:30,922
Dave Baronoff, you know...

2519
01:59:31,965 --> 01:59:33,341
Come on, April.
Should we talk about April?

2520
01:59:33,466 --> 01:59:34,551
No.

2521
01:59:34,676 --> 01:59:38,387
April cast the following people: John
Cho, she cast, Ben Cross, she cast...

2522
01:59:38,514 --> 01:59:41,100
April, who did and does <i>Lost...</i>

2523
01:59:42,141 --> 01:59:43,185
Are you taking your clothes off again?

2524
01:59:43,310 --> 01:59:44,560
- What is that sound?
- Seriously.

2525
01:59:44,685 --> 01:59:47,396
Sorry, sorry. I just took them back off.

2526
01:59:47,523 --> 01:59:50,192
- That's obviously the...
- Just as we're winding down.

2527
01:59:50,317 --> 01:59:52,985
- It's ending. Time to put...
- Get comfortable.

2528
01:59:53,112 --> 01:59:56,280
I'm sorry. I was anticipating Chris' nose.

2529
02:00:00,243 --> 02:00:03,122
I keep feeling like we should have done
something at the end of these credits,

2530
02:00:03,247 --> 02:00:05,623
because that's what all the crazy kids
are doing these days.

2531
02:00:05,748 --> 02:00:07,167
- I don't know what it is.
- I don't think so.

2532
02:00:07,292 --> 02:00:08,627
We had actually talked at one point

2533
02:00:08,752 --> 02:00:11,171
about doing something
at the end of the credits, you know...

2534
02:00:11,337 --> 02:00:12,338
The sequel.

2535
02:00:12,463 --> 02:00:15,884
...involving the Botany Bay,
but I'm glad we didn't,

2536
02:00:16,009 --> 02:00:19,137
because that would have tied our hands
for the sequel.

2537
02:00:19,262 --> 02:00:20,555
It would have.

2538
02:00:27,770 --> 02:00:30,440
Anything else we want to talk about
before we...

2539
02:00:30,565 --> 02:00:33,694
Is Gormley's name about to come out?

2540
02:00:34,153 --> 02:00:35,154
There he is.

2541
02:00:35,279 --> 02:00:37,613
I could literally talk about
Tommy Gormley for another two hours.

2542
02:00:37,738 --> 02:00:39,658
- Do your Tommy Gormley impression.
- I can't.

2543
02:00:39,783 --> 02:00:40,783
- Just do it.
- I can't.

2544
02:00:40,908 --> 02:00:46,664
But Tommy Gormley, who's the first AD,
he's Scottish and is just...

2545
02:00:47,832 --> 02:00:50,752
He did <i>Mission: Impossible III</i> with us
and is just the greatest.

2546
02:00:50,877 --> 02:00:54,213
And literally keeps it going,
you know, keeps the production going,

2547
02:00:54,338 --> 02:00:57,009
keeps everyone motivated
and, you know, working with him.

2548
02:00:57,134 --> 02:01:01,054
He's just the greatest.
And he has an amazing, beautiful family.

2549
02:01:01,180 --> 02:01:03,390
He's just a spectacular guy.

2550
02:01:05,057 --> 02:01:07,895
See, Gerald W. Abrams,
James McGrath, Jr. There they are.

2551
02:01:12,940 --> 02:01:14,818
Come on, someone? Bob?

2552
02:01:17,488 --> 02:01:21,158
I can't believe this worked.
I mean, it's like a time warp.

2553
02:01:21,283 --> 02:01:22,743
I just remember
when we all sat down with Nimoy

2554
02:01:22,868 --> 02:01:24,744
and we were like,
"Hey, how about we blow up Vulcan?

2555
02:01:24,869 --> 02:01:25,953
"How do you like that, my friend?"

2556
02:01:26,079 --> 02:01:27,747
- It's crazy that the...
- And now here we are.

2557
02:01:27,872 --> 02:01:31,335
You know, the movie has been out
for a month now

2558
02:01:31,460 --> 02:01:33,796
and people are going to see it.

2559
02:01:34,671 --> 02:01:36,840
More than once, which is weird.

2560
02:01:36,965 --> 02:01:38,926
The greatest thing ever is,

2561
02:01:39,051 --> 02:01:42,470
people are saying, "Oh, my God,
I dragged my wife to the movie,

2562
02:01:42,595 --> 02:01:46,809
"and she actually really liked it a lot."
So, again, that was the mission,

2563
02:01:46,934 --> 02:01:50,020
to get our wives to think
that <i>Star Trek</i> was cool.

2564
02:01:50,145 --> 02:01:54,858
Speaking of wives, I just want to say
that Majel Barrett-Roddenberry,

2565
02:01:54,983 --> 02:01:57,985
who we were honoured
to have visit the set

2566
02:01:58,112 --> 02:02:00,572
when we were shooting,
she was so wonderful.

2567
02:02:00,697 --> 02:02:05,661
She showed up and was supportive
and funny and sweet,

2568
02:02:07,121 --> 02:02:12,167
and she literally said, you know,
"Gene would love this."

2569
02:02:12,292 --> 02:02:15,796
Like she was just gracious,
and as supportive

2570
02:02:15,921 --> 02:02:19,591
as Nimoy was to Zach,
she was to me and the production.

2571
02:02:19,716 --> 02:02:23,970
And we all stopped and applauded her,
and it was really wonderful.

2572
02:02:24,095 --> 02:02:27,140
And we were lucky to get her
to do the voice of the computer,

2573
02:02:27,306 --> 02:02:28,975
Starfleet computer again.

2574
02:02:29,100 --> 02:02:34,480
And she, of course, sadly passed away
before we finished production. But...

2575
02:02:35,189 --> 02:02:36,692
And a few weeks after that
we had a nice call

2576
02:02:36,817 --> 02:02:39,110
from Eugene Roddenberry, their son,

2577
02:02:39,235 --> 02:02:41,822
who had seen the movie
and who said that

2578
02:02:41,947 --> 02:02:44,574
he felt his father would have absolutely
recognised it as <i>Star Trek,</i>

2579
02:02:44,699 --> 02:02:47,161
- and that he just loved it.
- That's awesome.

2580
02:02:47,286 --> 02:02:48,787
It's great to hear things like that.

2581
02:02:48,912 --> 02:02:54,542
Barney Burman, who, again, did a lot
of the makeup for the aliens and stuff,

2582
02:02:55,668 --> 02:03:01,425
his father is a famous
Hollywood makeup artist.

2583
02:03:01,550 --> 02:03:05,220
And I used to write letters
to musicians and makeup artists

2584
02:03:05,345 --> 02:03:06,430
and directors and stuff when I was a kid.

2585
02:03:06,555 --> 02:03:11,059
And I actually found, during production,
a letter from his father back to me.

2586
02:03:11,185 --> 02:03:12,895
And I brought it to the set one day

2587
02:03:13,020 --> 02:03:14,188
- and I said, "Dude, look at this."
- Oh, my God.

2588
02:03:14,313 --> 02:03:15,396
And he literally almost started crying.

2589
02:03:15,521 --> 02:03:16,648
- Of course he did.
- It was the greatest.

2590
02:03:16,774 --> 02:03:19,150
- I was like, "Can you believe this?"
- You don't pull that on someone...

2591
02:03:19,275 --> 02:03:21,153
- Oh, my God.
- It was some ridiculous thing

2592
02:03:21,278 --> 02:03:24,655
I'd written to him,
and he was so sweet to write me back.

2593
02:03:28,493 --> 02:03:31,872
It's amazing. Later you'll see
when the ILM credits come up

2594
02:03:31,997 --> 02:03:34,957
and you see the number of people
who work just at ILM.

2595
02:03:35,083 --> 02:03:39,046
I mean, obviously,
we had a huge construction crew

2596
02:03:39,171 --> 02:03:41,422
and the crew of the whole film,
hundreds of people.

2597
02:03:41,547 --> 02:03:46,052
But when you look at the ILM list alone,
it's shocking.

2598
02:03:46,886 --> 02:03:51,015
And they're just, they are brilliant.
I'm so grateful for the work that they do.

2599
02:03:51,140 --> 02:03:52,975
- It's incredible.
- We're going up there on Thursday.

2600
02:03:53,101 --> 02:03:55,229
- I'm really excited.
- Good.

2601
02:03:55,686 --> 02:03:56,979
- See, Roger Guyett.
- I've never been there.

2602
02:03:57,105 --> 02:03:59,399
- You're gonna lose your mind.
- What are you doing on Thursday, J. J?

2603
02:03:59,524 --> 02:04:02,485
- I'm supposed to go up to ILM. No.
- Nice.

2604
02:04:06,405 --> 02:04:11,537
Roger Guyett also shot
the second unit stuff,

2605
02:04:11,662 --> 02:04:14,288
which is usually right next door
to the main unit,

2606
02:04:14,414 --> 02:04:18,127
and he did so much amazing work.
It was just spectacular.

2607
02:04:21,171 --> 02:04:23,798
- We should make a sequel to this.
- I don't know, man.

2608
02:04:23,923 --> 02:04:27,719
We should do another one.
I think that'd be a lot of fun.

2609
02:04:27,845 --> 02:04:30,889
I had this impromptu meeting
with George Lucas before we shot,

2610
02:04:31,014 --> 02:04:32,432
and I said, you know...

2611
02:04:32,557 --> 02:04:35,435
- You just dropped a name.
- I know. Let me, I'm gonna pick that up.

2612
02:04:35,560 --> 02:04:39,273
And I was like, "What do I do?
How do I make this movie work?"

2613
02:04:39,398 --> 02:04:43,318
And he said, "Just put lightsabers in it."
Thank you.

2614
02:04:43,777 --> 02:04:45,069
- Is that what he said, really?
- Yeah.

2615
02:04:45,194 --> 02:04:46,613
- That's awesome.
- Digital artists.

2616
02:04:46,738 --> 02:04:48,532
So you might notice,

2617
02:04:48,657 --> 02:04:51,452
I think there's every name
in the world here. Look at this.

2618
02:04:51,577 --> 02:04:53,828
And each one of those people deserves,
like, a single card.

2619
02:04:53,953 --> 02:04:55,538
They're all amazing.

2620
02:04:55,663 --> 02:04:58,876
Going up there,
you'll see when you meet with them,

2621
02:04:59,001 --> 02:05:02,462
it's like walking past genius wizard
after genius wizard.

2622
02:05:02,587 --> 02:05:05,381
Like, they're just all amazing.
One guy does, like,

2623
02:05:05,506 --> 02:05:09,720
he'll do the, you know,
just the lens artefacts,

2624
02:05:09,845 --> 02:05:11,596
like the dirt on the lens,
and that's his thing.

2625
02:05:11,721 --> 02:05:13,640
- And someone else will do rotoscoping.
- Wow.

2626
02:05:13,765 --> 02:05:17,269
And they're all the best in the world
at what they... It's incredible.

2627
02:05:17,978 --> 02:05:19,061
The effects in this movie are incredible.

2628
02:05:19,188 --> 02:05:20,646
They really do put
everyone else to shame.

2629
02:05:20,773 --> 02:05:22,524
It's very painful not to work with them.

2630
02:05:22,649 --> 02:05:24,443
There are lot more names,
I think, coming.

2631
02:05:24,568 --> 02:05:27,069
Yeah, it's an amazing group. It really is.

2632
02:05:30,282 --> 02:05:32,743
Are you really still listening
